Verres, however, requires him to pay a sum of money as a guarantee ‘that he is not acquiring a livelihood by ‘chem’ offering to appoint some of his own retinue as arbiterS. Servilius proteste, and is ac- cordingly beaten to death. These are the facts that we gather from Cicero, but we know that no slave could be a party to a suit, and so we are met at the outset by a difficulty of ‘ Venerius servus.’ We must either accept Cicero's statements and make the best of them, or suppose that Verres treated the law with such contempt as to allow a slave, nominally at least, to appear as plaintiff ; though in this case it is not easy to see why he should try to give a legal colour to his proceedings at all.
